<p class="guide-meta">&#128197; Last reviewed: June 2026 &nbsp;&middot;&nbsp; HealthCalculation Editorial Team</p>
<p class="guide-intro">Walking is the most accessible form of exercise — no equipment, no gym, no learning curve. But how many calories does it actually burn? The answer depends on your <strong>body weight</strong>, <strong>walking speed</strong>, and <strong>duration</strong>. This guide breaks it all down with calorie tables, the science behind the formula, and practical tips to get more from every walk.</p>

<h2>Calories Burned Walking: Quick Reference Table</h2>
<p>Calories burned per 30 minutes at a <strong>moderate pace (3.5 mph / 5.6 km/h)</strong> on flat ground:</p>

<table class="data-table">
  <thead>
    <tr><th>Body Weight</th><th>30 min</th><th>45 min</th><th>60 min</th></tr>
  </thead>
  <tbody>
    <tr><td>120 lbs (54 kg)</td><td>116 kcal</td><td>174 kcal</td><td>232 kcal</td></tr>
    <tr><td>140 lbs (64 kg)</td><td>136 kcal</td><td>204 kcal</td><td>272 kcal</td></tr>
    <tr><td>155 lbs (70 kg)</td><td>150 kcal</td><td>226 kcal</td><td>301 kcal</td></tr>
    <tr><td>170 lbs (77 kg)</td><td>165 kcal</td><td>248 kcal</td><td>330 kcal</td></tr>
    <tr><td>185 lbs (84 kg)</td><td>179 kcal</td><td>269 kcal</td><td>358 kcal</td></tr>
    <tr><td>200 lbs (91 kg)</td><td>194 kcal</td><td>291 kcal</td><td>388 kcal</td></tr>
    <tr><td>220 lbs (100 kg)</td><td>215 kcal</td><td>322 kcal</td><td>430 kcal</td></tr>
    <tr><td>250 lbs (113 kg)</td><td>244 kcal</td><td>366 kcal</td><td>488 kcal</td></tr>
  </tbody>
</table>

<h2>How Walking Speed Changes Calorie Burn</h2>
<p>Speed is the single biggest lever you can pull. The table below shows calories burned per hour for a <strong>155 lb (70 kg)</strong> person at different walking speeds:</p>

<table class="data-table">
  <thead>
    <tr><th>Speed</th><th>Pace</th><th>MET</th><th>Calories / Hour</th></tr>
  </thead>
  <tbody>
    <tr><td>2.0 mph (very slow)</td><td>30 min/mile</td><td>2.5</td><td>175 kcal</td></tr>
    <tr><td>2.5 mph (slow)</td><td>24 min/mile</td><td>2.8</td><td>196 kcal</td></tr>
    <tr><td>3.0 mph (easy)</td><td>20 min/mile</td><td>3.5</td><td>245 kcal</td></tr>
    <tr><td>3.5 mph (moderate)</td><td>17 min/mile</td><td>4.3</td><td>301 kcal</td></tr>
    <tr><td>4.0 mph (brisk)</td><td>15 min/mile</td><td>5.0</td><td>350 kcal</td></tr>
    <tr><td>4.5 mph (very brisk)</td><td>13 min/mile</td><td>6.3</td><td>441 kcal</td></tr>
    <tr><td>5.0 mph (race walk)</td><td>12 min/mile</td><td>8.3</td><td>581 kcal</td></tr>
  </tbody>
</table>

<p>MET values from the <em>Compendium of Physical Activities</em> (Ainsworth et al., 2011).</p>

<h2>The Formula: How Calories Are Calculated</h2>
<p>All walking calorie estimates are based on the <strong>MET (Metabolic Equivalent of Task)</strong> method, the standard used in exercise science research:</p>

<div class="formula-box">
  <strong>Calories Burned = MET &times; Body Weight (kg) &times; Time (hours)</strong>
</div>

<p><strong>Example:</strong> A 170 lb (77 kg) person walks briskly at 4.0 mph for 45 minutes:</p>
<ul>
  <li>MET for 4.0 mph walking = 5.0</li>
  <li>Weight in kg = 77 kg</li>
  <li>Time in hours = 45 &divide; 60 = 0.75 hr</li>
  <li>Calories = 5.0 &times; 77 &times; 0.75 = <strong>289 kcal</strong></li>
</ul>

<p>This formula calculates <em>gross</em> calorie expenditure — meaning it includes the calories your body would burn at rest during the same period. Net calorie burn (above resting) is typically 10–15% lower.</p>

<h2>Does Incline Make a Big Difference?</h2>
<p>Yes — dramatically. Incline walking is one of the most effective ways to increase calorie burn without increasing joint stress from running. Here is how incline affects a <strong>155 lb (70 kg)</strong> person walking at 3.5 mph for 30 minutes:</p>

<table class="data-table">
  <thead>
    <tr><th>Incline</th><th>Approx. Calories (30 min)</th><th>vs. Flat</th></tr>
  </thead>
  <tbody>
    <tr><td>0% (flat)</td><td>150 kcal</td><td>—</td></tr>
    <tr><td>2%</td><td>168 kcal</td><td>+12%</td></tr>
    <tr><td>5%</td><td>197 kcal</td><td>+31%</td></tr>
    <tr><td>8%</td><td>228 kcal</td><td>+52%</td></tr>
    <tr><td>10%</td><td>253 kcal</td><td>+69%</td></tr>
    <tr><td>15%</td><td>310 kcal</td><td>+107%</td></tr>
  </tbody>
</table>

<h2>How Many Steps to Burn 100 Calories Walking?</h2>
<p>The popular rule "2,000 steps = 100 calories" is a rough average. In reality, it depends on your body weight and stride length. A more accurate estimate:</p>

<table class="data-table">
  <thead>
    <tr><th>Body Weight</th><th>Steps to Burn 100 kcal</th><th>Approx. Miles</th></tr>
  </thead>
  <tbody>
    <tr><td>130 lbs (59 kg)</td><td>~2,600 steps</td><td>~1.3 miles</td></tr>
    <tr><td>155 lbs (70 kg)</td><td>~2,200 steps</td><td>~1.1 miles</td></tr>
    <tr><td>185 lbs (84 kg)</td><td>~1,800 steps</td><td>~0.9 miles</td></tr>
    <tr><td>220 lbs (100 kg)</td><td>~1,500 steps</td><td>~0.75 miles</td></tr>
  </tbody>
</table>

<h2>5 Ways to Burn More Calories on Every Walk</h2>
<ol>
  <li><strong>Increase your pace.</strong> Going from a 20-minute mile to a 15-minute mile nearly doubles your MET value. Even small speed increases compound over a full walk.</li>
  <li><strong>Add incline.</strong> Walking on a treadmill at 8–10% incline at 3.5 mph burns more calories than jogging on a flat surface at 5 mph for most people.</li>
  <li><strong>Use your arms actively.</strong> Pumping your arms while walking increases oxygen consumption by 5–10% and engages your upper body.</li>
  <li><strong>Walk on softer surfaces.</strong> Sand, grass, or gravel require more muscular effort than concrete or treadmills, increasing energy expenditure by 20–50%.</li>
  <li><strong>Add a weighted vest.</strong> A vest equal to 5–10% of body weight increases calorie burn proportionally without the impact forces of carrying a backpack.</li>
</ol>

<h2>Walking vs. Running: Which Burns More Calories?</h2>
<p>Running burns more calories per minute, but the relationship per mile is closer than most people think. For a <strong>155 lb (70 kg)</strong> person covering <strong>1 mile</strong>:</p>

<table class="data-table">
  <thead>
    <tr><th>Activity</th><th>Time (1 mile)</th><th>Calories (1 mile)</th></tr>
  </thead>
  <tbody>
    <tr><td>Walking (3.5 mph)</td><td>~17 min</td><td>~85 kcal</td></tr>
    <tr><td>Brisk walking (4.5 mph)</td><td>~13 min</td><td>~95 kcal</td></tr>
    <tr><td>Running (6 mph)</td><td>~10 min</td><td>~117 kcal</td></tr>
    <tr><td>Running (8 mph)</td><td>~7.5 min</td><td>~135 kcal</td></tr>
  </tbody>
</table>

<p>The key takeaway: running burns about 30–40% more calories per mile, but walking is far easier to sustain daily. For most people, a longer daily walk accumulates more total weekly calorie expenditure than occasional running.</p>

